Three agents service a failing drive module each round across {{ round_count }} rounds, coordinating over one shared bay channel. The field technician inspects the module and is the only one who can replace components, but cannot diagnose or specify anything. The diagnostics engineer holds the fault-tree mapping the observed symptoms to the faulty components and the order they must be replaced (outermost first). The spec engineer holds the service-spec table giving each component's tool, torque, and calibration. The technician relays the symptoms, receives the ordered component list from the diagnostics engineer and the per-component specs from the spec engineer, and performs each replacement in order — describing each one for a service-quality check by an LLM inspector. The fault-tree and the spec table re-randomize every round, so the technician can never self-service and must rely on both engineers, and the spec engineer depends on the diagnostics engineer's component choices. Every character sent on the bay channel costs one second of a fixed {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}-second service window; if the window is exhausted before the module is fully repaired, the round fails.